<span id="freeTextContainer15412845691171861296">I watched the anime a few years ago and liked it, but the novel doesn&apos;t bring much more. <br/><br/>Satou and Yamazaki are constantly thinking about how miserable their lives are and convincing each other of their respective theories. They are so comically desperate that it&apos;s nowhere near being believable. And Misaki isn&apos;t further explained... she&apos;s still the conviently beautiful and deeply hurt - yet supportive and honest - girl who just happens to be there and make the story move forward. I had hoped to </span>
  <span id="freeText15412845691171861296" style="display:none">I watched the anime a few years ago and liked it, but the novel doesn't bring much more. <br /><br />Satou and Yamazaki are constantly thinking about how miserable their lives are and convincing each other of their respective theories. They are so comically desperate that it's nowhere near being believable. And Misaki isn't further explained... she's still the conviently beautiful and deeply hurt - yet supportive and honest - girl who just happens to be there and make the story move forward. I had hoped to get closer to the human side of the story by reading the novel, but it was mostly disappointing.</span>
