  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2404736605" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2404736605" />
    <a title="Jon Ureña" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3073125-jon-ure-a"><img alt="Jon Ureña" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610203917p2/3073125.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2404736605?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jon Ureña" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jon Ureña" href="/user/show/3073125-jon-ure-a">Jon Ureña</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3073125-jon-ure-a?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3073125-jon-ure-a?shelf=mental-illness">mental-illness</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2404736605" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13109189609455757176">Four and a half stars.<br/><br/>This story, whether in its anime, manga or original novel format, has become a somewhat obscure cult classic that many of those familiar with other works don&apos;t even know, and many others, that haven&apos;t experienced to some degree the psychic pains the characters in this story have to live with, can&apos;t stomach it. When I read <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2443502312?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1' rel='nofollow noopener'>the manga (link to the first of its volumes I reviewed)</a> I realized that the anime was a softer version of the manga version, and now that I&apos;ve read the no</span>
  <span id="freeText13109189609455757176" style="display:none">Four and a half stars.<br /><br />This story, whether in its anime, manga or original novel format, has become a somewhat obscure cult classic that many of those familiar with other works don't even know, and many others, that haven't experienced to some degree the psychic pains the characters in this story have to live with, can't stomach it. When I read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2443502312?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">the manga (link to the first of its volumes I reviewed)</a> I realized that the anime was a softer version of the manga version, and now that I've read the novel, which I'm currently reviewing, I realize that the manga was a much softer version of the original 2001 novel.<br /><br />The story revolves around three main characters: Tatsuhiro Satou, a twenty two year old self professed <i>hikikomori</i> who was born with or developed early on some psychological peculiarities that caused him to spiral down since high school until he had to drop out of college during the first year, because his anxiety and paranoia had grown to the extent that he couldn't stand being near people. When we meet him he has spent his last four years holed up in a "six-mat one-room apartment", sustaining himself through the allowance his out of town parents send him. The second character is Misaki Nakahara, a mysterious eighteen year old girl that we meet through her Christian missionary job as she, along with her zealot aunt, happen to knock on Satou's door. The third character is Kaoru Yamazaki, a twenty one year old <i>otaku</i> with an extremely short fuse and a sexual predilection for elementary school girls.<br /><br />In addition we have Satou's high school <i>senpai</i> Hitomi Kashiwa, whom he met through the literature club, where he spent a year playing cards with her and having weird conversations. Hitomi is portrayed as a model-like beauty but afflicted with something like a schizotypal personality disorder and self-destructive tendencies. Most conversations she had with Satou involved her going on about the conspiracies she detected in the world, and how disparate subjects were somehow connected. She was one of the most memorable elements of the manga and the anime, but I was surprised to discover that she barely had two fleshed out scenes in the original novel. That means that one of the best sequences of the anime/manga, where <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[she decides to travel far away to off herself in a mass suicide, along with Satou who believed he was just going on a pleasurable vacation <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, is completely absent.<br /><br />At its core this is a pitch-dark comedy, something like a less ambitious Japanese "Fight Club" (the movie came out just two years earlier), in which we follow outcasts who are unable, due to accidents of birth or casual circumstances, to find their place in society, and who constantly struggle to figure out how they are going to spend the rest of their lives, or if they are going to keep living at all.<br /><br />The plot kicks in when Misaki, a mysterious missionary girl, pursues Satou into meeting each other regularly in a nearby park so he can participate in her project to rehabilitate <i>hikikomori</i>, a sort of people that the girl repeatedly refers to as the most worthless kind. Through Satou's efforts to adjust to this intrusion he experiences some progress. First he lies compulsively about his life to hide his pitiful state, something he does to some degree throughout the entire story, but watching his miserable life reflected on this girl, he <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[attempts and fails to get a part time job in a nearby manga cafe <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. He realizes that his next door neighbor who blasts anime songs is none other than his high school pal Yamazaki, whom he met through attempting to save him from a beating that Yamazaki himself started. The guy wants to become an animator; <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[although in the manga and anime we see him attending related classes, and we meet some of his classmates, in this original version he seemingly just attended a few classes and quit, if he even got in to begin with and it wasn't just a delusional dream of his. He's something of a <i>hikikomori</i> as well, but somewhat experienced in developing amateur games <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Because Satou was trying to deceive Misaki into believing that he had a freelance job as a "creator", <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[both guys agreed to make a game. Unfortunately, Yamazaki could only see himself developing an erotic game, a genre to which he was somewhat addicted, and more damningly, the objects of conquest had to be elementary school girls, according to his sexual predilections. While in the anime and manga versions this fact is diluted to some degree, the original novel doesn't shy away from it in any way. Yamazaki rambles on about how monstrous adult women are, mostly because he had bad experiences with some, and extols the innocent qualities and unspoiled bodies of elementary school girls. He pushes Satou to do some research on them so they can develop their game better, and Satou ends up holed up in his apartment for a week gathering around 30GB of erotic photos of real elementary girls. Conscious of how monstrous he's become and the dangerous path he's threading, with his delusional logic he drags Yamazaki into visiting a local school and photographing the girls as they come out; he believed that behaving like the worst kind of pervert in the real world would wake him up and make him come back to acceptable sexual preferences (like the crush he had on his high school <i>senpai</i>, the only girl he had sex with). And it works, mostly because Misaki happened to come by and he ended up having to explain himself to her <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />We go through several meetings between Satou and Misaki. They meet at night in a nearby park, and she shares passionately everything she has researched about self-help, psychological therapy and philosophy. Despite her earnestness, the author did a brilliant job depicting Misaki's at this point <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[implicitly broken home life and her own psychological troubles through the inept job she does at cobbling the information together: she presents some of the information as if she hadn't learned basic popular knowledge through mandatory schooling, and all the books she lends to Satou she seemed to have chosen to solve her own psychological issues. Satou feels that nothing is changing and that he's not going to be "cured" at all, but he doesn't really care, because being able to talk with her most nights, at least for an hour or so, gives him some energy. I had a somewhat similar experience with therapy myself, until eventually the ratio of money spent to relief experienced went way off <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Satou and Yamazaki spend most of their time, and allowances, on drugs, mainly hallucinogens. This was completely absent in the anime probably because it would face a somewhat mainstream audience in television. The author goes on about the drugs they take with very technical details, and the believable and bizarre sequences in which both characters are drugged out of their minds suggest that the author was depicting his own experiences.<br /><br />There are three sequences in the novel that are missing in the other versions of this story. All of them are risky, and likely were cut from the manga and anime because the editors involved in those industries are generally more touchy. In the first of those sequences, Satou, wanting to figure out once and for all if Misaki getting involved with him was just part of her missionary work, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[infiltrates along with Yamazaki a meeting in their headquarters, where Misaki was going to give a speech about the results of her "research". We meet many of the Christian fundamentalists involved in that organization; they go on about how they fight against Satan and the impending Apocalypse, and they must oppose evil even in those who unwittingly do Satan's bidding. Misaki behaves with these people like a shy mouse. She clearly doesn't want to be involved. Later on she explains herself: she lives with her aunt and uncle, and the woman dragged her into it. Misaki admits that she doesn't believe in God, that if God existed it had to be an evil God, because her life had been nine parts pain to one of joy. She said that she wished that God existed; in that case she could simply blame all the miseries in her life on that entity instead of feeling that everything is her own fault. During that conversation we learn about the burn marks on her arms that hint to a terrible previous home life. This whole conversation was used during one of the last episodes of the anime <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />The second of those sequences involves Yamazaki <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[building a bomb, which he calls a Revolution Bomb, that he would use to kill some politician; he needed to blame someone for his terrible life. I'm guessing they cut this out of both the manga and the anime because terrorism. However, in reality he had intended to blow his own head off with the bomb, but when they light it up in the nearby park it explodes like a bunch of firecrackers, which leaves Yamazaki depressed <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />In the third of these sequences, Satou and Yamazaki <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[enact their own "Fight Club". To feel alive through the pain, they beat each other up in the park everyone visits constantly. They hit hard, and by the end both end up severely bruised and bloody. Misaki stops them. Through her reaction to the violence, and how she flinches at Satou's shadow boxing, we realize that she must have been beaten regularly throughout her life. It speaks to the author's skill that Satou doesn't connect the dots at all; in fact, he seems amused at Misaki's reaction <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />The story approaches enters its last stretch when Misaki <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[opens up about the purpose and motivation of her project: because of how she had suffered at the hands of her parents, mainly her stepfather, she had ended up believing it was all her fault for being useless, broken, a bother to everyone. Years ago she had had to quit school because she suffered constant panic attacks. Her project was a desperate attempt not only to connect with someone broken that she could understand, but through figuring out how to cure him, manage to find a cure for herself as well. However, this was a hope that she didn't really believe, and behind it all she had been planning to kill herself: she would do something good for someone broken, therefore having had a positive effect on the world, and then she would kill herself by throwing herself off the cape from where her mother had jumped many years ago. At that point, however, it was a fate she would rather avoid, so she attempts in desperation to entangle Satou in a "companionship contract" that would force him to be with her whenever she felt lonely, which was all the time. Satou, still terrified of personal relationships, and believing himself to be venomous, tells her that she'll do fine if she just looks up instead of feeling sorry for herself all the time, and quits the project <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />By this point, Satou's parents hadn't been sending him allowance for a good while. Satou (big spoilers for the ending) <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[tried to spend as little money as possible by fasting and sleeping a lot, but by the end he ended up taking part-time jobs. He could barely stand them, and he got into a routine of working for a while and then spending some time off living off his savings, but it's something that he wouldn't have been able to do if Misaki hadn't brought him out of the shadows a bit. He spends close to a year apart from the girl, not knowing anything about how she was doing, only to casually find out she had just attempted to off herself by swallowing a lot of sleeping pills, an amount that she would have amassed through pretending to take regular medication that some psychiatrist must have been giving her. Satou goes to visit her in the hospital, but she has escaped. He understands, through the suicide note she left and some research she had been doing on train times, that she was going to travel to her hometown and throw herself off a cliff. Satou travels there immediately and in a heartfelt sequence he, someone who had wanted to die for his entire life, has to convince someone he's ended up appreciating that she must go on living. In his somewhat delusional state, Satou reveals to her the role of the organization that he had convinced himself was behind everyone's pain, and he attempts to blow it up in a suicide charge (<a href="https://youtu.be/mxvh3GYdlgk?t=552" rel="nofollow noopener">this is that moment in the anime, in its early 2000s, mid tier production glory</a>). Through facing the fear of losing someone she appreciated as well, she decides to go on living. She writes up her last contract: one in which they vow to live for the sake of each other, to try as hard as they can to find some happiness in their lives <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Despite the events of the climax, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[everyone moves forward except for Satou. Yamazaki, having failed to make something valuable of his video game, moves back to his family's farm, and manages to settle down in an arranged marriage with a girl of his liking (an adult this time). Satou's high school <i>senpai</i> attracts a millionaire through her good looks and, despite being a self-destructive weirdo, gets married and pregnant. Misaki herself goes to college and presumably ends up having a decent enough life. Satou remains a <i>hikikomori</i>, holed up in his apartment, although he earns his living through various part time jobs. The implicit lesson of this story is that your fate in life will mostly depend on accidents of birth and/or casual events, and the most you can do is choose to endure it to its inevitable end <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />The author's life didn't have a happy ending either. Although he's still alive, in his early forties, in an afterword to the novel he explains that he wrote it to get out of his <i>hikikomori</i> state, but five years later he still was one, living off royalties, and he hadn't found the strength to write anything else: whenever he attempted it he faced a terrible fear, as if he was going to commit himself to a mental institution, as if he had given himself some sort of PTSD through writing it. He hasn't written anything else in the close to fifteen years that have passed, which is a real tragedy.<br /><br />I suspect the author of the masterful <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2963358706?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">"Oyasumi Punpun"</a> went through something similar, and, without comparing qualities, I experienced it as well after writing my last two books. The stories I'm most attracted to give you the sense that through them their authors had attempted to claw their way out of hell, and once they've gotten what they needed out of them, having "cured" themselves or not, attempting something similar again feels like torture.<br /><br />I've exhausted the character limit for the review, but I might mention some other stuff in the comments.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13109189609455757176" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


