    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1775307019" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1775307019" />
    <a title="Matthew Sarabando" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59888567-matthew-sarabando"><img alt="Matthew Sarabando" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1775307019?book_show_action=true">Oct 03, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Sarabando" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Sarabando" href="/user/show/59888567-matthew-sarabando">Matthew Sarabando</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1775307019" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2813392280967915420">As a person who watch/read both the anime and manga (respectively), I can honestly say that the manga was better. Not only did it include some plot points that I didn&apos;t know about, it gave me a fresh look into the series as a whole. Like with the anime, it was emotionally gripping. You really get to sympathize with the main cast as a whole because they were written to mimic real people and situations that anyone could get into. Of course I can&apos;t go into them cause that would be spoiling some plo</span>
  <span id="freeText2813392280967915420" style="display:none">As a person who watch/read both the anime and manga (respectively), I can honestly say that the manga was better. Not only did it include some plot points that I didn't know about, it gave me a fresh look into the series as a whole. Like with the anime, it was emotionally gripping. You really get to sympathize with the main cast as a whole because they were written to mimic real people and situations that anyone could get into. Of course I can't go into them cause that would be spoiling some plot points, but I'll try to do my best to give basic summaries of each plot point without giving details and ruining the experience that you're meant to have reading a book.<br />However, I do have to question some of the intelligence of some of the characters at play here. Satō specifically, I get that he's supposed to be a NEET (Not in Education, Employment, or Training) and a hikikomori and therefore lack some social knowledge that would help his situation, but c'mon. To give an example, during one of the arcs he literally saw through one of the tricks, but then after some more sweet talk, gives in to the trick. C'mon, you saw through it, got what the character(s) was supposed to be doing in order for them to have the sweeter deal, yet you still fall for it. But I chalk that up to it being rushed, granted it was kind of out of character, but in the end it did improve the relationship between Satō and Misaki, whether that's a good or bad thing is completely up to interpretation.<br />Now how are the characters as a whole? I feel as though they all have noble intentions, but they don't have the ability to actually come off as a good person in the end. Misaki specifically comes off as manipulative and selfish (you'll find out the reasons why). Yamazaki (the third person as part of the main cast), has his moments sure, but there are times where he comes off as rude or just as manipulative. Don't get me wrong though, he wants so much to finish the game he and Satō have been doing the entire time, but the things he does can seem a little extreme at sometimes. To avoid yet another plot spoiler, lets just say that he can be meaner that he looks. And finally, the main character Satō, written to be a true hikikomori. It's very, VERY, easy to sympathize or at least empathize with him because he represents the (stereotypical) anime fan. Right off the bat, you learn how he basically distance himself from society and relies solely on the income of his parents. Now I don't mean to discriminate, but when this manga was released, the anime fan was your 300 pound, NEET, unsocial, etc. etc, person. Now the anime fan has since been improved to be a legitimate respectable hobby now. So longtime fan of anime will easily see where Satō comes from while the newer audience will have some trouble actually giving a damn about him. This is my interpretation, I could be wrong.<br />For everything else, like story, development, mood, tone, I describe it as emotionally gripping and that's all I need to say cause going further on I could get into some spoiler territory but I shall refrain. But yeah, I totally would recommend this book to people who either have experience with manga and anime or people who just like psychological aspects mixed in with some romance and some good writing. 4/5 - Nice read </span>
  <a data-text-id="2813392280967915420" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


