<div id="review_78540527" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/78540527" />
    <a title="Beth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/774519-beth"><img alt="Beth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1205601661p2/774519.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/78540527?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beth" href="/user/show/774519-beth">Beth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/774519-beth?shelf=teen-ya-fiction">teen-ya-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer78540527" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14330546694411315598">First off, yes, this is a Japanese *novel,* not a manga, despite the manga-style cover. There is a manga version of the story also.<br/><br/>I classified this as a &quot;teen&quot; book despite the main character being an adult, because it has many elements that will appeal to older teens. Our (anti-) hero is a 22-year-old &quot;hikkikomori,&quot; a person who has pretty much withdrawn from life--dropped out of school, no job, no social life. The book deals in an understated yet realistic way with the phenomenon, as well as </span>
  <span id="freeText14330546694411315598" style="display:none">First off, yes, this is a Japanese *novel,* not a manga, despite the manga-style cover. There is a manga version of the story also.<br /><br />I classified this as a "teen" book despite the main character being an adult, because it has many elements that will appeal to older teens. Our (anti-) hero is a 22-year-old "hikkikomori," a person who has pretty much withdrawn from life--dropped out of school, no job, no social life. The book deals in an understated yet realistic way with the phenomenon, as well as depression, questionable use of legal drugs, and suicidal thoughts. WARNING: one of the characters is seriously into lolicon (sexual fascination with preteen girls).<br /><br />The author's style (as best as one can judge from a translation) is simple and emotionally low-key. He identifies himself as a hikkikomori. Definitely a dark-humor elements.<br /><br />For liberal-minded older teens and adults who like "problem novels" or stories about bizarre people. Anime and gaming fans who have hikkikomori tendencies themselves may find it appealing. I doubt this book will appear in many public libraries because of the lolicon and drug elements.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14330546694411315598" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


