              <span id="reviewTextContainer259740872" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14386136647148762661">While truly quite funny at times this book totally bummed me out. I simply see too much of myself in Satou. I&apos;ve been somewhat of a hikikomori since I graduated college last May and there are indeed times when I feel as though fate is conspiring to marginalize me. I say this only to attest to the accuracy of Satou&apos;s feelings throughout the novel. It made me sadder still to read the afterwords of this book, which make it apparent that Satou&apos;s struggle is very much the author&apos;s struggle as well, a</span>
  <span id="freeText14386136647148762661" style="display:none">While truly quite funny at times this book totally bummed me out. I simply see too much of myself in Satou. I've been somewhat of a hikikomori since I graduated college last May and there are indeed times when I feel as though fate is conspiring to marginalize me. I say this only to attest to the accuracy of Satou's feelings throughout the novel. It made me sadder still to read the afterwords of this book, which make it apparent that Satou's struggle is very much the author's struggle as well, and that he continued to struggle some years after writing it. I can't think of a very good way to end this review other than saying that this is a very good book, and if you are capable of being sad it will likely make you so, especially if you are a hikikomori.</span>
