    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2464513244" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2464513244" />
    <a title="George Edward" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84440194-george-edward"><img alt="George Edward" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546826812p2/84440194.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2464513244?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="George Edward" class="user" itemprop="url" name="George Edward" href="/user/show/84440194-george-edward">George Edward</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2464513244&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2464513244" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15873287724139456832">The anime that this book inspired helped save my life. No joke, I was an American “hikikomori” and every day I wondered what the purpose of my<br/>life was, and why I was so “worthless.” Soon, three years passed and my growing fear of my all of my failures gave rise to anxiety so bad I couldn’t even enter crowded areas. After watching Welcome to the NHK, I realized that not only was I not the only one who suffered from this grief, but that I could find the answer of how to save myself. There isn’t a </span>
  <span id="freeText15873287724139456832" style="display:none">The anime that this book inspired helped save my life. No joke, I was an American “hikikomori” and every day I wondered what the purpose of my<br />life was, and why I was so “worthless.” Soon, three years passed and my growing fear of my all of my failures gave rise to anxiety so bad I couldn’t even enter crowded areas. After watching Welcome to the NHK, I realized that not only was I not the only one who suffered from this grief, but that I could find the answer of how to save myself. There isn’t a universal answer to stop being a hikikomori. Everyone who suffers from anxiety can only fix it by finding out and realizing the tools to their own happiness. People realize they can change, and when they truly believe it they can change. Every day is still a struggle, but you learn more and more little by little, and the memories of being unable to do anything for yourself become a distant life. <br /><br />What it comes down to, is that this book (and the manga and anime) does such a good job highlighting what someone like Satou goes through. It’s one of the few books that goes into such painful detail of anxiety, depression and not fitting in. It highlights the terrible parts of mental disorders, the parts that those who suffer through it live through every day. The odd anime porn, revolutionary bomb, and drug subplots only add more to Satou’s struggles to find out who he is. In the end, they are merely ways for himself to divert his attention, to try and trick himself into thinking that he can actually feel like a normal person. The book explains coping mechanisms of someone who suffers with suicidal thoughts by letting you experience every inner monologue, trip, and tangent alongside Satou. <br /> <br />Just a warning, Welcome to the NHK doesn’t have a traditional satisfying ending. It is fitting however, because depression is a constant battle. In both afterwords, the author speaks of these same feelings he shares with Satou. The author still suffers with being a hikikomori. I really appreciated the realistic view he put into this book. It shows the path Satou went through in trying to accept himself and his failures.<br /><br />I recommend this book for those who might be or have suffered with depression, extreme loneliness, and anxiety. It helped me learn how to understand myself better, and helped me feel a little less alone in the worst of times. It’s not perfect by any stretch of the imagination, and the translation could have used some refinements. Overall, if you can find it (seriously good luck), give it a shot.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15873287724139456832" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

