    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2574057210" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2574057210" />
    <a title="Ihsan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51699036-ihsan"><img alt="Ihsan" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2574057210?book_show_action=true">Oct 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ihsan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ihsan" href="/user/show/51699036-ihsan">Ihsan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2574057210" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer718135361698502015">Welcome to the NHK is a terrifying novel.<br/><br/>It’s not written as horror or anything, and most people will feel no dread as they flip through its pages: that doesn’t matter though. Our main character Satou here exemplifies so many characteristics that I personally relate to and H A T E about myself (e.g. a fear of others laughing at you as you walk by, constant feelings of uselessness, a lack of drive or ambition) that my skin can’t help but crawl as I peer into the abyss of the hikekomori lifestyle.</span>
  <span id="freeText718135361698502015" style="display:none">Welcome to the NHK is a terrifying novel.<br /><br />It’s not written as horror or anything, and most people will feel no dread as they flip through its pages: that doesn’t matter though. Our main character Satou here exemplifies so many characteristics that I personally relate to and H A T E about myself (e.g. a fear of others laughing at you as you walk by, constant feelings of uselessness, a lack of drive or ambition) that my skin can’t help but crawl as I peer into the abyss of the hikekomori lifestyle. I’m a high school student preparing to enter into college, and seeing this complete failure of a man drop out and seclude himself in his dark room, his only companion being an old high school acquaintance who even scares him sometimes with his short temper and passion for degeneracy, makes me afraid of what I could become. Even those who seem to have their lives together like the young girl Misaki and the cute upperclassman he once met are severely fucked. Nobody gets out of this game we call life unscathed.<br /><br />I suppose you’d want me to do a plot synopsis or something here but this story doesn’t need a plot. It’s pretty much a series of short events explaining Satou’s life situation that happen to be chronologically ordered and lead to a climax at the end anyways.<br /><br />This is not a story for the faint of heart. If you relate to Satou’s shortcomings, prepare for a variable emotional journey that continues on even into the second afterward. If you cannot relate to him and hi she struggles, you may find yourself hating him and, by proxy, the book as a whole. I relate and so I am terrified. Terrified for my future, for what may come to pass, but excuses will get me nowhere.<br /><br />The tatami Galaxy taught me a similar lesson: nothing will change unless you do. There is no one to blame for what your situation is besides yourself. The comfort that comes will faultlessnes is not worth the stagnation it brings. These are stories I hope to carry with me into my college years so that I can live a somewhat happy life, or at least narrowly dodge the future that Welcome to the NHK foresees.</span>
  <a data-text-id="718135361698502015" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


